The mx and the nb commands work together.  The duration of a block of
audio data and the total number of blocks are interdependent.  Changing
one changes the other.  You can change them with either of these two
commands, ms (milliseconds), or nb (number of blocks).  The minimum
duration of a block is one millisecond, called an atom of sound, and
the minimum number of blocks is two.  By default, block durations are
1000 milliseconds, or one second in length, and the total number of
blocks is therefore determined by the file size.  Type either ms or nb,
press space, type the desired value, and press enter.  If you type either
command without specifying a value, the current settings are reported.

